<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-bolzano-weierstrass"
xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Bolzano-Weierstrass Theorem</title>

  <p>
    Consider a sequence <m>(x_n)</m>. For each <m>k \in \N</m>, let
    <m>S_k := \{x_n : n \ge k\}</m> be the set of all terms of
    <m>(x_n)</m> with index at least <m>k</m>. Clearly
    <m>S_k \supseteq S_{k+1}</m>, and so
  
  <me>
       \inf S_{k} \le \inf S_{k+1} \le \sup S_{k+1} \le \sup S_{k}
  </me>
  
    as extended real numbers. Since any two of the sets <m>S_k</m> differ by
    only finitely many terms, either all of them are bounded or none of them
    is. In the bounded case, the real sequence <m>(\sup S_k)_k</m> is
    decreasing and bounded below by <m>\inf S_1</m>. By the Monotone
    Convergence Theorem, this sequence has a limit. That limit is called the
    <term>limit superior</term> of <m>(x_n)</m> and is denoted by
    <m>\limsup x_n</m>. Likewise, the <term>limit inferior</term> of
    <m>(x_n)</m> is defined to be the limit of the real sequence
    <m>(\inf S_k)_k</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    If the sets <m>S_k</m> are not bounded above, then each
    <m>\sup S_k = +\infty</m>, and we define <m>\limsup x_n = +\infty</m>.
    Likewise, if the sets <m>S_k</m> are not bounded below, then each
    <m>\inf S_k = -\infty</m>, and we define <m>\liminf x_n = -\infty</m>.
  </p>

  <proposition xml:id="prop-convergent-iff-limsup-equals-liminf">
    <statement>
      <p>
         A bounded sequence <m>(x_n)</m> is convergent if and only if
	 <m>\limsup x_n = \liminf x_n</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
      <p>
        Suppose first that <m>x_n \to L</m>. Let <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m>.
        Choose <m>N\in\N</m> such that for all <m>n\ge N</m>,
	<me>
	L -\varepsilon \lt x_n \lt L + \varepsilon.
	</me> 
        
	Then for any <m>k \ge N</m>, <m>S_k \subseteq (L-\varepsilon,
	L+\varepsilon)</m> and so

	<me>
	L-\varepsilon \le \inf S_k \le \sup S_k \le L+\varepsilon.
	</me>

	Therefore, <m>\limsup x_n=\lim_k \sup S_k</m> is arbitrary closed
	to <m>L</m> and hence must be <m>L</m>. Likewise, <m>\liminf x_n =
	L</m> as well.
      </p>

      <p>
        Conversely, suppose <m>\liminf x_n = \limsup x_n = L</m>. Since
        <m>x_k\in S_k</m>, we have 
	<me>
          \inf S_k \le x_k \le \sup S_k
        </me> for every <m>k</m>. By the squeeze lemma, <m>x_k \to
        L</m>. Therefore <m>(x_n)</m> is convergent.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </proposition>

  <p>
    One of the main ways in which the completeness of <m>\R</m> enters the
    study of sequences is through the following theorem.
  </p>

  <theorem xml:id="thm-bolzano-weierstrass">
    <title>Bolzano-Weierstrass Theorem</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Every bounded sequence of real numbers has a convergent subsequence.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
      <p>
	For a bounded sequence <m>(x_n)</m>, we construct a subsequence as
	follows: set <m>n_1:=1</m>. Suppose natural numbers <me> n_1 \lt n_2
	\ldots \lt n_k </me> have been chosen for some <m>k \ge 1</m>. By
	the definition of supremum, there is some natural number <m>n_{k+1}
	\ge n_k + 1 \gt n_k</m> such that
	
	<men xml:id='inductive-step'>
            \sup S_{n_k +1} - \frac{1}{k} \le x_{n_{k+1}} \le \sup S_{n_k +
	    1}.
	</men>
	This inductively defines a strictly increasing sequence <m>(n_k)</m>
	of natural numbers and hence a subsequence <m>(x_{n_k})</m>
	of <m>(x_n)</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
	As a subsequence of the convergent sequence <m>(\sup S_n)</m>,
	<m>(\sup S_{n_k+1})</m> also converges to <m>\limsup x_n</m> by <xref
	ref="prop-subsequence-of-convergent-sequence"/>. Since the sequence
	<m>(\sup S_{n_k+1} - 1/k)</m> has the same limit, the squeeze lemma
	applied to <xref ref="inductive-step"/> shows that <m>x_{n_{k+1}}
	\to \limsup x_n</m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </theorem>

  <p>
    In fact, we proved a stronger statement: every bounded sequence contains a
    subsequence that converges to its limit superior, and likewise a
    subsequence that converges to its limit inferior. With a slight
    modification of the proof, one can also show that if a sequence is not
    bounded above (respectively, below), then it has a subsequence that
    diverges to <m>+\infty</m> (respectively, <m>-\infty</m>).
  </p>

  <proposition xml:id="prop-subsequence-liminf-limsup-inequalities">
    <statement>
      <p>
         For any subsequence <m>(x_{n_k})</m> of a sequence <m>(x_n)</m>,
	 <me>
             \liminf_n x_n \le \liminf_k x_{n_k} \le \limsup_k x_{n_k} \le
	     \limsup_n x_n. 
	 </me>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
      <p>
        For each <m>n\in\N</m>, let <m>S_n:=\{x_m:m\ge n\}</m>, and for each
        <m>k\in\N</m>, let
        <me>
          T_k:=\{x_{n_j}:j\ge k\}.
        </me>
        Then <m>T_k\subseteq S_{n_k}</m>, so
        <me>
          \inf S_{n_k} \le \inf T_k \le \sup T_k \le \sup S_{n_k}
        </me>
        for every <m>k</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        If <m>(x_n)</m> is not bounded above, then
        <m>\sup S_n=+\infty</m> for every <m>n</m>, and so
        <m>\limsup_n x_n=+\infty</m>. In that case the last inequality is
        automatic. Otherwise <m>(x_n)</m> is bounded above, so
        <m>(\sup S_n)</m> is a real decreasing sequence converging to
        <m>\limsup_n x_n</m>. Since <m>(\sup S_{n_k})</m> is a subsequence of
        <m>(\sup S_n)</m>, it has the same limit by
        <xref ref="prop-subsequence-of-convergent-sequence"/>. Also,
        <m>\sup T_k \le \sup S_{n_k}</m> for every <m>k</m>, so
        <m>\limsup_k x_{n_k} \le \limsup_n x_n</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        Similarly, if <m>(x_n)</m> is not bounded below, then
        <m>\inf S_n=-\infty</m> for every <m>n</m>, and so
        <m>\liminf_n x_n=-\infty</m>. In that case the first inequality is
        automatic. Otherwise <m>(x_n)</m> is bounded below, so
        <m>(\inf S_n)</m> is a real increasing sequence converging to
        <m>\liminf_n x_n</m>. Since <m>(\inf S_{n_k})</m> is a subsequence of
        <m>(\inf S_n)</m>, it has the same limit. Also,
        <m>\inf S_{n_k} \le \inf T_k</m> for every <m>k</m>, so
        <m>\liminf_n x_n \le \liminf_k x_{n_k}</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        Finally, <m>\inf T_k \le \sup T_k</m> for every <m>k</m>, so
        <m>\liminf_k x_{n_k} \le \limsup_k x_{n_k}</m>. Combining the three
        inequalities gives the result.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </proposition>

  <p>
    We conclude this section with a proof of the Bolzano-Weierstrass theorem
    that uses only convergence, not limit superior or limit inferior. Its main
    advantage is that it is more visual.
  </p>

  <proposition xml:id="prop-monotone-subsequence">
    <title>Monotone Subsequence Lemma</title> <statement>
      <p>
        Every real sequence has a subsequence that is either increasing
        or decreasing.
      </p>
    </statement>

    <proof>
    <p>
     Let <m>(x_n)</m> be a real sequence. Call <m>n\in\N</m> a
     <term>peak index</term> if <m>x_n\ge x_m</m> for every <m>m\ge n</m>.
    </p>
      <p>
        First suppose there are infinitely many peak indices. Choose them in
        increasing order:
        <me>
          n_1 \lt n_2 \lt n_3 \lt \cdots.
        </me>
        Since <m>n_k</m> is a peak index and <m>n_{k+1}\ge n_k</m>, we have
        <m>x_{n_k}\ge x_{n_{k+1}}</m> for every <m>k</m>. Hence
        <m>(x_{n_k})</m> is a decreasing subsequence.
      </p>

      <p>
        Now suppose there are only finitely many peak indices. Then there is
        some <m>n_1\in\N</m> such that no <m>n\ge n_1</m> is a peak index.
        Since <m>n_1</m> is not a peak index, there exists <m>n_2\gt n_1</m>
        such that <m>x_{n_2}\gt x_{n_1}</m>. Since <m>n_2</m> is not a peak
        index, there exists <m>n_3\gt n_2</m> such that
        <m>x_{n_3}\gt x_{n_2}</m>. Continuing inductively, we obtain a
        subsequence <m>(x_{n_k})</m> with
        <me>
          x_{n_1} \lt x_{n_2} \lt x_{n_3} \lt \cdots.
        </me>
        Therefore <m>(x_{n_k})</m> is increasing.
      </p>

      <p>
        In either case, <m>(x_n)</m> has a monotone subsequence.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </proposition>

  <p>
    By the lemma above, every sequence has a monotone subsequence. If the
    original sequence is bounded, then this subsequence is also bounded. A
    bounded monotone sequence converges by
    <xref ref="thm-monotone-convergence"/>, so the Bolzano-Weierstrass theorem
    follows.
  </p>
</section>
